ARRAYS
=========================================================================================================================================================================================================

- Arrays are fundamental data structures in programming that allow you to store a collection of elements of the same type under a single variable name.
- In C#, arrays have fixed sizes, meaning once you declare an array with a certain size, you cannot change its size.


DECLARATION OF ARRAYS
---------------------
Syntax: <Data Type> [ ] <Array_Name>
eg: int[] x;  // can store int values
    string[] s; // can store string values
    Student[] stud1; // can store instances of Student class which is custom class


INITIALIZATION OF ARRAYS
------------------------
An array is a reference type so the new keyword used to create an instance of the array.
Syntax: type[ ]  <Array_Name> = new  <datatype>[size];
eg: int[] y= new int[5] 


<<<<<<<<PROPERTIES>>>>>>>>>>>
1.ACCESSING ELEMENTS
------------------
You can access individual elements of an array using square brackets [].
Array indices start from 0.

2.LENGTH PROPERTY
-----------------
The Length property returns the total number of elements in the array.

3.LOOPING THROUGH AN ARRAY
-------------------------
You can use loops like for or foreach to iterate over array elements.


TYPES
------
1.Multi-dimensional Arrays: 
You can create arrays with multiple dimensions.

2. Jagged Arrays:
Jagged arrays are arrays of arrays where each element can be an array itself.





